To fix the code quality issue of having a console.log statement in production code, you should remove the console.log statement from the code. 

Here is the updated code without the console.log statement:

```typescript
// src\app\api\marketing\leads\route.ts

// Some existing code here

// This endpoint is used to retrieve leads
router.get('/leads', async (req: Request, res: Response) => {
  try {
    const leads = await Lead.find();
    res.status(200).json(leads);
  } catch (error) {
    console.error('Error retrieving leads:', error);
    res.status(500).send('Internal server error');
  }
});

// Some existing code here
```

By removing the console.log statement and using console.error instead, you can maintain the error logging functionality without logging unnecessary information to the console in production.